    "m72TourSection": {
      "title": "The M72 World Tour: Lars at 62",
      "content": "Metallica's M72 World Tour (2023-2025) represents an unprecedented feat in rock history: a band in their fifth decade headlining stadiums worldwide with two completely different setlists per city.\n\nFor Lars Ulrich at 62 years old, this means playing 2.5+ hour shows, often two nights in a row, with completely different songs each night. The stamina required is remarkable — most drummers half his age couldn't maintain this schedule.\n\nThe M72 configuration keeps Lars's setup road-ready while honoring the visual spectacle Metallica is known for. The drums sit on a riser that allows for dramatic lighting effects, and the configuration remains consistent enough that Lars can perform reliably across dozens of shows.\n\nWhat's notable is how Lars has adapted his playing for longevity. While early Metallica was played at blistering tempos, modern live performances often sit in a slightly more sustainable pocket. This isn't \"slowing down\" — it's playing smart, prioritizing 25+ songs per night over brief bursts of unsustainable speed.\n\nThe M72 Tour also features Lars performing \"72 Seasons\" material alongside classics spanning their entire career. From \"Hit the Lights\" (1983) to \"Lux Æterna\" (2023), Lars is playing four decades of material nightly — a testament to both his adaptability and the timelessness of Metallica's drum parts.",
      "keyPoints": [
        "2.5+ hour shows, two different setlists per city",
        "Stadium tours at 62 years old",
        "Performs material spanning 40+ years",
        "Adapted playing for longevity without sacrificing power",
        "Most ambitious tour in Metallica's history"
      ]
    },
