      "description": "For Load, Lars Ulrich upgraded from the Tama Artist Maple used on the Black Album to the Tama Star Classic Maple — Tama's premier maple offering, positioned above the Artist line in construction quality, shell refinement, and acoustic performance. The Star Classic's enhanced maple shell construction delivered greater warmth, projection, and sustain than the Artist Maple, well-suited to Load's open, blues-influenced production aesthetic and the breathing space Bob Rock created at The Plant Studios.\n\nThe Star Classic's improved bearing edges and shell construction allowed the maple to resonate more freely than the Artist series — a property that Bob Rock exploited by placing room microphones to capture the kit's full acoustic voice alongside the standard close microphones. The Plant Studios' large recording room was a key asset: the Star Classic could develop its full resonance before the ambient mics caught the sound, resulting in drum tracks with depth and dimension that the more compressed Black Album approach did not pursue.\n\nThe kit configuration followed Lars's Black Album template closely: a 22\" bass drum driven by a double pedal, 10\" and 12\" rack toms, and 14\" and 16\" floor toms. This was Lars's standard configuration since 1991, and the continuity allowed him to focus on the gear's sonic qualities rather than relearning an unfamiliar setup. Tom tuning for Load was slightly lower and warmer than the Black Album — suiting the album's more laid-back, blues-influenced character — while retaining the presence the maple construction provided.\n\nLoad's recording process was notably extended even by Metallica's standards. Sessions at The Plant Studios and Prairie Sun Recording stretched from early 1995 through early 1996, giving Lars more time with the Star Classic than any previous Metallica studio project. This extended familiarity is audible in the recordings: the drum performances on Load, while less technically complex than earlier albums, are exceptionally settled and confident, exploiting the Star Classic's natural acoustic qualities with the assurance that comes from months of studio time together.\n\nOne historical note for researchers: the Tama Star Classic (mid-1990s era) predates the later product renamed Tama Starclassic (one word) — the naming conventions across the eras can cause confusion, but Load-era documentation consistently references the Star Classic Maple as Lars's primary recording kit during 1995–1996. The two lines share a philosophy of maple flagship construction but represent distinct product generations.",
