        "question": "Why did Metallica change their sound so dramatically on Load?",
        "answer": "Load's stylistic shift — from thrash metal toward blues-influenced hard rock — was a deliberate artistic decision by the band. James Hetfield has cited influences including Bob Seger, ZZ Top, and Neil Young on the songwriting direction. For Lars's drumming specifically, producer Bob Rock continued pushing him in the direction begun on the Black Album: away from technical complexity and toward feel, groove, and serving the song above all else. Load's songs, with their pentatonic riffs and slower tempos, demanded different drumming than the thrash-era material — and Lars's adoption of the Tama Star Classic Maple and Zildjian A Custom cymbals supported a production approach oriented toward natural warmth and room ambience rather than the compressed, close-miked thrash sound. Commercially, the gamble paid off: Load debuted at #1 on the Billboard 200 and went 5× Platinum in the United States."
