      "description": "For the St. Anger sessions, Lars Ulrich moved away from the Tama Artist Maple and Starclassic kits he had used through the Black Album, Load, and ReLoad eras and worked with DW to assemble a custom Collector's Series Maple kit at HQ — the Metallica-owned facility located inside the Presidio in San Francisco. The kit was finished in black with chrome hardware, matching the visual aesthetic the band had established for the record.\n\nThe configuration was a true double bass setup — two 22\" x 18\" kick drums rather than a single kick with double pedal. This was a deliberate choice for St. Anger's relentless, often surf-tempo-meets-thrash kick patterns: two independent drums project two independent attacks, with the physical mass of dual shells producing a heavier low-end footprint in the room than a single kick with double pedal can replicate. Tracks like \"Frantic,\" \"St. Anger,\" and \"Some Kind of Monster\" depend on this kind of sustained dual-kick weight.\n\nThe tom configuration was deliberately spartan compared to Lars's Black Album and Load-era spreads. A single 12\" rack tom over the hi-hat side, with two floor toms (14\" and 16\") on the right, reduced the kit to its functional core for a record whose drum sound philosophy was about raw impact rather than melodic tom orchestration. DW's Hard Rock Maple shell construction provided the attack and projection necessary for the dry, close-miked production approach the album required.",
