      "description": "For Hardwired...to Self-Destruct, Lars Ulrich anchored his setup on the DW Collector's Series Maple kit — the kit that defined his sound across the Death Magnetic touring cycle and into the Hardwired sessions. Where the earlier Tama Starclassic Birch had emphasized attack and punch, the DW Collector's Series Maple offered a wider tonal palette: warmer fundamentals, longer sustain, and the kind of fullness that suited Hardwired's heavier, riff-dense arrangements.\n\nThe defining choice for Hardwired was the move to dual 22\" × 18\" bass drums. Lars had spent decades running a single 22\" kick with an Iron Cobra double pedal, but the dual-kick configuration on Hardwired delivered tonal consistency and visual presence that matched the album's renewed thrash ambitions. Each bass drum could be tuned independently, allowing subtle character differences between the two, and the dual-kick rig eliminated the slight mechanical compromises inherent to slave-beater double pedals.\n\nDW's VLT (Vertical Low Timbre) shell construction, where the outer ply is cut so the grain runs vertically rather than horizontally, produces a lower fundamental pitch than traditional horizontal-grain shells. The result on Hardwired is a kit that hits with more low-end body than the Starclassic Birch of Death Magnetic — fuller toms, kick drums with deeper thump, and a snare drum that sat in a more cushioned environment.\n\nLars kept his tom configuration economical for Hardwired: a single 12\" rack tom up top with 14\" and 16\" floor toms below. This is the same minimal tom setup he has favored since the Justice era — Lars's playing has always emphasized kick-snare interaction over tom flurries, and the limited tom array reflects that priority. When the toms do appear, as in the fills throughout \"Atlas, Rise!\" and the explosive moments in \"Spit Out the Bone,\" they punctuate rather than decorate.\n\nDW's True Pitch tuning system gave Greg Fidelman the precise lug-by-lug control needed to dial in consistent fundamental pitches across every drum at HQ studio. Combined with Evans heads tuned for attack and the room treatment Metallica had developed at their own facility, the kit sound on Hardwired stands among the most refined Lars has ever committed to record.",
