    "conclusion": {
      "title": "Hardwired: The Modern Lars Ulrich Configuration",
      "content": "Hardwired...to Self-Destruct captures Lars Ulrich at a confident moment in his modern career — playing the most sustained uptempo material Metallica had recorded since the Black Album era, on a refined cross-brand kit that combined DW shells, Zildjian cymbals, Tama pedals, Evans heads, and Ahead sticks into a single coherent setup. The album sits cleanly within the Black Album → Death Magnetic → Hardwired arc: each record represents Lars at a particular gear and production juncture, with Hardwired delivering the most polished synthesis of the three.\n\nThe DW Collector's Series Maple kit, dual 22\" × 18\" bass drums, and Tama Speed Cobra pedals became Lars's established touring rig from 2016 onward — through the WorldWired Tour and into Metallica's subsequent activity. The combination of self-production at HQ studio and Greg Fidelman's punchy modern engineering produced a drum tone that avoided the Loudness War controversy of Death Magnetic while delivering the kind of weight and attack that the material demanded.\n\nFor drummers studying Lars Ulrich's modern setup, the Hardwired configuration is the reference. The gear is achievable: DW Collector's Series Maple remains in production, Zildjian A Custom and Z Custom cymbals are widely available, Tama Speed Cobra HP910 pedals remain a standard choice for working drummers, and Evans heads are everywhere. What's less replicable is the context — three decades of Metallica drumming refined into the configuration that worked, and a self-owned studio environment with unlimited time for sound refinement.\n\nFor the full Lars Ulrich gear story across the modern era, see the [Lars Ulrich drummer profile](/drummer/lars-ulrich), the [Black Album drum setup](/articles/black-album-drum-setup), and the [Death Magnetic drum setup](/articles/death-magnetic-drum-setup). For broader context on the band, see the [Metallica band page](/band/metallica). For comparison with the modern thrash drumming landscape, the [thrash metal drummers guide](/articles/thrash-metal-drummers) and the [Big Four drummers analysis](/articles/big-four-drummers) cover Lars's peers and contemporaries."
    },
